<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-819-820  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 819 820.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Sept 1990 v15 n9 p28(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>EFF: bringing Bill of Rights into the computer age. (ElectronicFrontier Foundation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fisher, Sharon.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Mitch Kapor, founder of Lotus, and a number of his industrycolleagues have established the Electronic Frontier Foundation toeducate government policymakers, law enforcement officials, andthe public at large about computers and to ensure that violationsof civil liberties, with respect to computers, do not gounchallenged.andP;  Some members of the industry see the EFF as a'hacker defense fund' and many law enforcement officials expresspuzzlement over why the computer industry would defend people thattry to break into systems, but Kapor says this is not the purposeof the EFF.andP;  Rather, it will support efforts toward ensuring thatthe freedoms provided by the Bill of Rights are extended toelectronic as well as paper information.andP;  Among the EFF's firstactions was the extension of a grant to Computer Professionals forSocial Responsibility, which will use the funds in its Computingand Civil Liberties Project.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Statute:   United States Constitution. 1st-10th Amendments (interpretationand construction).andO;Topic:     Computer CrimesElectronic Frontier Foundation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>